# Rules Organization Standards

## File Structure
- All cursor rule files must be placed in the `.cursor/rules` directory
- Use the `.mdc` extension for all rule files
- Keep rule files focused on specific concerns
- Group related guidelines in a single rule file

## Naming Conventions
- Use kebab-case for rule filenames (e.g., `code-quality.mdc`, `api-standards.mdc`)
- Choose descriptive names that clearly indicate the rule's purpose
- Avoid generic names that don't convey specific content

## Metadata Requirements
- Every rule file must include metadata at the top between `---` delimiters
- Required metadata fields:
  - `description`: Brief explanation of the rule's purpose
  - At least one of:
    - `alwaysApply`: Set to true if rule should always be included
    - `globs`: File patterns the rule applies to

## Content Organization
- Start with a clear title using a level 1 heading
- Use level 2 headings for major sections
- Use lists for specific guidelines
- Keep rules concise and actionable
- Include examples for complex guidelines when helpful

## Rule Updating Process
- When editing rules, create a temporary file first to ensure proper formatting
- Once the content is validated, move the file to the correct location in `.cursor/rules`
- If having trouble with direct edits, use the terminal to copy the file to its correct location
- Always validate that the rule file was successfully updated after making changes
- Never include comments or sections that aren't relevant to the specific rule file
- When editing existing rules, maintain the established structure and formatting

## Integration of Custom Standards
- Project-specific standards should be generalized and integrated into existing general rule files when possible
- Create new rule files only when standards don't fit within existing categories or are highly specific to certain uses.

## Maintenance
- Review and update rules regularly
- Remove or update obsolete guidelines
- Consider creating specialized rules for specific technologies or components
